Here is the implementation guide. Firebase Studio is your development environment, **Firebase App Hosting** is the production runtime for the master application, and **Cloudflare** is the runtime for the open-source tools. That split is the sane one. It keeps identity, memberships, and Google integrations on the Firebase side, and keeps the OSS products as satellite applications instead of turning your main repo into a landfill. Firebase documents that App Hosting is the recommended deployment path for full-stack Next.js apps, and that App Hosting runs builds through Cloud Build, serves the app from Cloud Run, and integrates with other Firebase services. Cloudflare documents that Workers can run on custom domains, that Node.js compatibility is available via nodejs\_compat, and that full server-style workloads can be run through Cloudflare Containers.

Your current repository already matches that model. The repo is a **Next.js app created in Firebase Studio** according to README.md, firebase.json is configured for **Firebase App Hosting**, package.json includes next, firebase, and firebase-admin, src/firebase/server.ts initializes the Admin SDK with Application Default Credentials in production, and src/lib/data.ts plus src/lib/entitlements.ts already model users, membership plans, membership access grants, and tier-based entitlement logic. Your current middleware.ts only marks /admin/\* requests and does not yet enforce member-tool access flows, so tool launch authorization needs to be implemented server-side in new route handlers.

1\. System model
----------------

Use a **control plane / workload plane** design.

The **control plane** is rbp-master-application on Firebase App Hosting. It owns:

*   authentication
    
*   membership plans and status
    
*   entitlement evaluation
    
*   Google account linking
    
*   tool registry
    
*   launch token issuance
    
*   provisioning orchestration
    
*   audit logging
    

The **workload plane** is the set of Cloudflare-hosted OSS tools. Each tool owns:

*   its own UI and runtime
    
*   tool-specific business logic
    
*   tenant-scoped or workspace-scoped data
    
*   a local session created from a trusted launch event
    
*   optional calls back to the master app for Google operations or account provisioning
    

The master app should be the only source of truth for “who is this user, what plan do they have, what tool can they access, and which workspace belongs to them.” Your existing Firestore user and entitlement model already points in that direction. src/lib/data.ts maps user fields like membershipTier, membershipStatus, membershipPlanCode, billingCycle, accessExpiry, and Square references, while src/lib/entitlements.ts already computes effective tier and allowed access levels for tools and content.

