6\. Launch-token contract
-------------------------

The master application should not forward Firebase tokens straight into tools and hope for the best. Firebase ID tokens are for identifying users to your backend and other Firebase-aware services; Firebase documents that server-side backends should verify them before trusting them. Use them only on the Firebase side. The tool should receive a **short-lived launch token** issued by the master application after the master application has already verified the user and membership.

### 6.1 Browser redirect flow

The browser redirect flow should be:

1.  user clicks tool tile in master app
    
2.  browser hits POST /api/tools/:toolKey/launch
    
3.  master app verifies rbp\_session
    
4.  master app resolves membership tier, grants, and tool mapping
    
5.  master app provisions user/workspace if needed
    
6.  master app signs a one-time or very short-lived JWT
    
7.  browser is redirected to https://tool.example.com/auth/launch?token=...
    
8.  tool verifies JWT and creates a local session cookie
    
9.  tool redirects the user into their workspace
    

### 6.2 Launch token claims

Use an asymmetric JWT signed by the master app. Suggested claims:

