9\. Google API integration model
--------------------------------

Keep Google identity and Google tokens on the Firebase side. Do **not** let each tool invent its own Google OAuth flow unless you want the kind of support burden that makes people fantasize about farming.

### 9.1 Why the master app should broker Google APIs

Firebase App Hosting runs on Google infrastructure, supports Admin SDK auth through ADC, and the backend service account can be granted additional Google roles. That makes the master app the right place to centralize Google API connectivity.

### 9.2 Google broker design

The member links Google once, inside the master app. Then the master app stores:

*   linked Google account metadata
    
*   granted scopes
    
*   encrypted refresh token or delegated credentials
    
*   mapping from user to approved Google resources
    

The Cloudflare tool never stores Google refresh tokens. Instead it calls a broker endpoint on the master app:

*   POST /api/internal/google/drive/list
    
*   POST /api/internal/google/sheets/read
    
*   POST /api/internal/google/docs/create
    

Each request includes:

*   tool service identity
    
*   end-user identity
    
*   tenant/workspace context
    
*   requested operation
    
*   correlation ID
    

The master app validates:

*   the calling tool
    
*   the member’s current entitlement
    
*   whether the member linked a Google account
    
*   whether the requested Google scope is allowed for that tool
    
*   tenant ownership of the requested Google resource
    

Then the master app performs the Google API call and returns only the scoped result.

### 9.3 Service-to-service auth for broker calls

Do not use browser tokens for this.

Use a tool service credential:

*   one shared secret per tool, stored in Cloudflare Secrets and Google-side secrets
    
*   or a private key per tool if you want asymmetric service auth
    

The tool signs a short-lived service JWT like:

