11\. Route protection in the master application
-----------------------------------------------

Your current middleware.ts only touches /admin/\* and adds a header. That is not enough for member-tool launches.

Do this instead:

*   keep middleware lightweight
    
*   verify tool access server-side in route handlers
    
*   optionally extend middleware to redirect unauthenticated users away from /dashboard and /tools
    
*   never depend on hidden buttons as access control
    

The important authorization decisions happen in:

*   /api/auth/\*
    
*   /api/tools/\*
    
*   /api/internal/\*
    

12\. Cloudflare application patterns
------------------------------------

### 12.1 Worker-native tool

Use this when the tool:

*   is mostly TypeScript/JavaScript
    
*   does not require a traditional server process
    
*   can work within Worker constraints
    

### 12.2 Container-backed tool

Use Cloudflare Containers when the tool:

*   is packaged as a container
    
*   expects a server process
    
*   needs local listening ports or persistent in-container behavior
    

Cloudflare’s Containers docs describe using a Container class to route requests into a container instance and forward traffic to its default port.

### 12.3 Compatibility testing checklist

Before you adopt a tool, verify:

*   required Node modules
    
*   filesystem behavior
    
*   child process expectations
    
*   websocket expectations
    
*   native binary requirements
    
*   background job model
    
*   tenant model
    
*   branding flexibility
    
*   auth replaceability
    

Cloudflare’s own Node compatibility docs make it clear that some Node APIs are partial or shimmed, so you need this test up front.

13\. Recommended implementation sequence
----------------------------------------

### Phase 1: harden the master app

Implement:

*   Firebase Auth session-cookie endpoints
    
*   tools\_catalog, tool\_accounts, tool\_launch\_audit
    
*   canAccessTool() and tool-specific entitlements
    
*   launch JWT signing
    
*   JWKS endpoint
    
*   internal Google broker stubs
    
*   internal provisioning stubs
    

### Phase 2: onboard one pilot tool

Pick the easiest candidate:

*   clean codebase
    
*   some tenancy concept
    
*   configurable login
    
*   low-risk data model
    

Then add:

*   /auth/launch
    
*   tenant session handling
    
*   local cookie session
    
*   provisioning integration
    
*   broker client for Google operations
    

### Phase 3: standardize adapters

In the master repo, create:

*   src/lib/tool-adapters/base.ts
    
*   src/lib/tool-adapters/planner.ts
    
*   src/lib/tool-adapters/crm.ts
    

Every adapter implements:

*   ensureAccount()
    
*   buildLaunchClaims()
    
*   getRequiredTier()
    
*   getBaseUrl()
    
*   allowedGoogleScopes()
    

### Phase 4: lifecycle events

Add workflows for:

*   signup
    
*   upgrade
    
*   downgrade
    
*   cancel
    
*   suspend
    
*   re-activate
    
*   global signout
    

When membership changes, update tool\_accounts and optionally call tool-side lifecycle endpoints.

14\. Operational and security controls
--------------------------------------

Use these as non-negotiables:

*   Launch JWT TTL: 60 seconds max
    
*   Local tool session TTL: 8 to 12 hours max
    
*   All cookies: HttpOnly, Secure, SameSite=Lax unless cross-site flows require None
    
*   Log every launch and broker call with correlation IDs
    
*   Never store master private keys in git
    
*   Never let browser specify tenantId
    
*   Never let tools store Google refresh tokens
    
*   Re-verify membership on every launch, not just on signup
    
*   Revoke tool access when account is suspended or membership lapses
    

Firebase documents revocation controls for sessions and ID tokens, so use them during account suspension and security events.

